	<li>Resource sharing</li>
	<li>Grid computing</li>
</ul>
<h3>Topic Area: Web Services and Middleware</h3>
<p>Web services have become an essential tool for enhancing the development and integration of technology applications. The term &quot;Web services&quot; refers to a collection of technologies that facilitates access to and integration of modular applications using a browser as access to a set of automated interfaces. With the proliferation of portals and the increased use of thin-client technologies, every institution will eventually become both a supplier and consumer of Web services. Quality of service is a significant factor in distinguishing the usability, utility, and value of service providers. Many institutions are using Web services to support best-of-breed strategies, as well as to extend the usability of legacy applications. Identity management, authorization, directory services, and other middleware strategies such as Shibboleth are key to appropriately managing the emerging distributed services environment. </p>
<p>Key topics include:</p>
<ul>
	<li>Suppliers and consumers of Web services</li>
	<li>Quality of service</li>
	<li>Modular applications</li>
	<li>Reusable and interoperable functionality</li>
	<li>Standard ubiquitous protocols (HTTP, XML)</li>
	<li>Web services architecture</li>
	<li>Dynamic integration</li>
	<li>Middleware</li>
	<li>Identity management and authorization</li>
	<li>Shibboleth and Shibbolized applications</li>
	<li>Directory services (LDAP, ActiveX, NDS)</li>
	<li>Java</li>
	<li>.NET</li>
	<li>Portals</li>
</ul>
<h2>Track 6: Protecting The Data: Security, Policy, And Privacy</h2>
<h3>Topic Area: Security Technology/Infrastructure</h3>
<p>Higher education recognizes the vital role IT plays in an institution's mission and has developed expertise in dealing with the challenge of protecting diverse user communities of students, researchers, administrators, and other users, as well as their applications, data, systems, and enterprise networks. The academic IT world can both learn from and provide information to the commercial IT environment regarding security architecture, technology, and tools. </p>
<p>Key topics include:</p>
<ul>
	<li>Network security, registration, and access control</li>
	<li>Identity management, authentication, and authorization (Shibboleth)</li>
