<h2>Track 7: Teaching And Learning</h2>
<h3>Topic Area: Assessment and Evaluation</h3>
<p>Teachers can't employ teaching and learning technologies effectively unless they have reliable and meaningful measures of learning outcomes. Students' learning styles vary, and information technologies offer both teachers and students unprecedented flexibility and options for customization, but instructional strategies depend on good assessment tools if progress is to be made in instructional design or learning design support models. At a time of declining public funding for education and increasing calls for educational accountability, thoughtful, multisource assessment of the effectiveness of teaching and learning technologies is a vital factor in strategic planning at all levels of the enterprise. </p>
<p>Key topics include:</p>
<ul>
	<li>Electronic assessment</li>
	<li>Course assessment</li>
	<li>Online testing and survey</li>
	<li>Instructional design</li>
	<li>Learning outcomes</li>
	<li>Learning models</li>
	<li>Assessment of learning outcomes</li>
	<li>Assessment of teaching</li>
	<li>Pedagogy</li>
	<li>Performance evaluation</li>
	<li>Evaluative studies</li>
	<li>E-portfolios</li>
	<li>Assessment practices</li>
	<li>Course redesign</li>
	<li>Assessment designs</li>
	<li>Academic policies</li>
	<li>Instructor/student needs assessment</li>
</ul>
<h3>Topic Area: Digital Course Content</h3>
<p>Developing, finding, using, and sharing digital course content requires a new mix of resources, skills, and collaborations. Current theories of learning must be integrated with technology; systems and architectures must enable content to be reused or shared; and innovative models for collaboration must allow faculty to build and use content easily. Libraries, in particular, are central to the process because of their expertise in identifying existing resources, in assisting with research for new content, and in creating standardized access to new digital products and content. </p>
<p>Key topics include:</p>
<ul>
	<li>Learning objects</li>
	<li>Multimedia content</li>
	<li>Course redesign and curricular development</li>
	<li>Production teams and project management</li>
	<li>Best practices for teaching and learning with digital content</li>
	<li>Collaboration</li>
	<li>Learning management systems</li>
	<li>Accessibility</li>
	<li>Content sharing</li>
	<li>Content management</li>
	<li>Scalability</li>
	<li>Standards</li>
	<li>Metadata</li>
	<li>Copyright</li>
	<li>Open access</li>
	<li>E-learning research</li>
	<li>Digital asset management</li>
	<li>Repositories</li>
	<li>New media/rich media authoring</li>
</ul>
<h3>Topic Area: Online Learning: Distributed, Distance, and Blended Learning Environments</h3>
<p>Distance and distributed education have grown more complex and inclusive as blended learning environments emerge from combinations of online learning and residential classroom settings. One-way transmission of course content has become a mixture of synchronous and asynchronous interactivity, often with students collaborating electronically outside sessions convened by the instructor. What are the possibilities and challenges of these new models of online learning? How does increasingly sophisticated student multimedia authoring fit into instructor-generated course content? What role do instructional designers play in crafting distance, distributed, and blended learning environments? How can instructors and instructional designers be compensated fairly for the course content and design they contribute to the institution? How can schools cooperate to deliver, assess, and grant credit for online learning? What role do commercial partners play in supporting the costs of developing and delivering online learning? </p>
<p>Key topics include:</p>
<ul>
	<li>Distributed and distance learning</li>
	<li>Mobile learning</li>
	<li>Interactive and self-paced learning environments</li>
	<li>Web-based instruction or courses</li>
	<li>Collaboration tools</li>
	<li>Computer-mediated student-faculty and student-peer relationships</li>
	<li>Course or digital content development</li>
	<li>Pedagogical best practices</li>
	<li>Remote examinations and proctoring models</li>
	<li>Remote help desk and support mechanisms</li>
	<li>Delivery of library and other student services</li>
	<li>Strategic planning</li>
	<li>Cost-effectiveness and ROI standards</li>
	<li>Learning outcome assessment and evaluation</li>
</ul>
<h3>Topic Area: Faculty Development, Incentives, and Engagement</h3>
<p>Higher education remains committed to the strategic use of information technologies in teaching and learning, but without opportunities for careful study and professional development, faculty cannot find or implement the truly transformative uses for these technologies. Moreover, colleges and universities will need to move beyond early adopters and other low-hanging fruit to find ways to encourage reluctant or skeptical faculty to experiment with these technologies as well. How do we align development resources with faculty who are ready to grow in these areas, both as disciplinary specialists and as teachers? What opportunities are most attractive to faculty: released or reassigned time, stipends, local or national consortia, project-based development, or some combination of all of these? How can academic support professionals partner most effectively with faculty to realize the goals of integration and transformation? How can institutions of higher learning best demonstrate their commitment to innovation and achievement in these areas? In terms of skills in the use of teaching and learning technologies, what should departments look for as they recruit new faculty for a new generation of students? Crucially, how can criteria for tenure and promotion recognize and reward faculty accomplishments in these areas? </p>
<p>Key topics include:</p>
<ul>
	<li>Faculty support models</li>
	<li>Faculty engagement techniques</li>
	<li>Assessment of teaching effectiveness</li>
	<li>Course development teams</li>
	<li>Faculty mentoring</li>
	<li>Student mentoring</li>
	<li>E-portfolios or digital portfolios</li>
	<li>Faculty recruitment and hiring</li>
	<li>Institutional policies regarding technology and teaching</li>
	<li>Faculty promotion and tenure</li>
	<li>Incentives, rewards, and recognition</li>
	<li>Community of practice</li>
	<li>Scholarship of teaching</li>
	<li>Release/reassigned time</li>
	<li>Competency-based learning</li>
	<li>External grant support</li>
	<li>Faculty roles</li>
	<li>Faculty development</li>
	<li>Consortia</li>
	<li>Low-threshold applications</li>
</ul>
<h3>Topic Area: Support and Skill-Building</h3>
<p>As information technologies grow more pervasive in teaching and learning, scalable support and training models for students, faculty, and staff are more essential than ever. Without reliable support, students and faculty will be reluctant to use these technologies in their work; without skill-building programs, they will be unable to use these technologies effectively. Without skilled and confident faculty, students, and staff, higher education cannot offer an information-saturated society any hope of mastering the tools of information literacy and digital fluency. Likewise, support and training are essential if faculty are to grow and thrive as professionals within an increasingly online knowledge environment in which their disciplines require increasingly sophisticated uses of information technologies. </p>
<p>Key topics include:</p>
<ul>
	<li>Cost-effectiveness</li>
	<li>Information literacy</li>
	<li>Digital fluency</li>
	<li>Spatial thinking</li>
	<li>Help desk</li>
	<li>Scalable support</li>
	<li>24 x 7 support</li>
	<li>Just-in-time support</li>
	<li>Online support</li>
	<li>Faculty development and staff training</li>
	<li>Student training</li>
	<li>Support staff training</li>
	<li>Training centers</li>
	<li>Support/training staff retention</li>
	<li>Problem Tracking</li>
	<li>Business support models</li>
	<li>Outsourcing</li>
	<li>Multimedia support</li>
	<li>Research support</li>
	<li>Classroom support</li>
	<li>Tools of the discipline</li>
	<li>Collaborative support models</li>
</ul>
<h3>Topic Area: Student Life</h3>
<p>Understanding the characteristics and aptitudes of higher education learning constituencies-in both formal and informal learning and social contexts-is key to establishing constructive frameworks for the use of technology in teaching and learning. Student use of information technologies, often driven by innovations in consumer electronics, takes students into virtual worlds (often networked) of increasing complexity and sophistication. Students often appear more invested in these virtual spaces than they are in their real classrooms. How might these technologies, experiences, and energies be harnessed for higher education? What balance should instructors seek between inviting these technologies into the classroom and excluding them from formal learning? How can disruptive technologies such as wireless or peer-to-peer file transfers shape our understanding of student life? </p>
<p>Key topics include:</p>
<ul>
	<li>Social software (Facebook, MySpace, LiveJournal)</li>
	<li>Extracurricular projects</li>
	<li>Learning styles and aptitudes</li>
	<li>Cultural approaches to technology</li>
	<li>Informal vs. formal learning spaces and practices</li>
	<li>Student authoring</li>
	<li>New findings in the science of learning</li>
	<li>Persistent virtual worlds</li>
	<li>Massively multiplayer online role-playing games</li>
	<li>Continuous partial attention</li>
</ul>
